{"text": "When I first started playing Dungeon of the Endless- Crystal Edition, I wasn't having much success. After several tries to get going on the game, I kind of put it aside for a bit. However, I was determined to figure the game out as from what I did play of the game I thought I would enjoy it. So I decide to watch a video of a couple of employees of Amplitude play the game. This helped greatly and I have now completed runs three or four times now. Dungeon of the Endless is a nice mixture of Tower Defense, Rogue Like, RPG and strategy. The game has two skill levels, too easy and easy. Don't let this fool you as too easy is a real challenge itself. The developers having a little joke with the levels. When you start the game you have a limited number of ships (dungeons) and characters to play. As you play you open up more ships and characters til you have a normal total of eight ships and twenty-six characters. As you make your way through the dungeon you can find equipment that your characters can use as well as places to set resource generators, merchants, dust, characters to add to your team and of course monsters. Gathering resources allows you to buy equipment, level your characters, research modules, heal characters and build modules. The ships you choose to play on have different modifiers on them affecting the way you play so you can have many different challenges, giving the game more re-playability. Your main goal is to get as many resources as possible and to level up and equip your characters to make the long journey through 12 levels of each ship. With the big challenge of taking a crystal that is at your start room of each level, all the way to the exit of each floor , with one of your (hopefully) speedy characters. The game has an old school look to it, along with some very nice music and good sound effects as well. As, I mentioned at the start the game is quite the challenge, do not think you will jump right in and win right away and every time.If you like a nice challenge and some extra special dungeon crawling, I highly recommend this game.", "appid": "249050", "steamid": "profiles/76561198030756861", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "63", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1587902400.0}
{"text": "My first Yakuza game, and I gotta say, this is one hell of a first impression. This is easily one of the best beat 'em up games ever made. The story is gripping and interesting, the protagonists, Kiryu and Majima, are both lovable and hilarious, the combat is brutal, fast-paced and hilarious, and the side quests are both hilarious and occasionally wholesome. There are so many things to do in this game, like I am honestly astounded at the amount of minigames that Yakuza 0 has. You can sing karaoke, do disco, play pool or darts, go bowling, etc. and stuff like Cabaret Czar and Real Estate are addicting and make you lots of money.  The only negatives I have with this game are the keyboard controls, save feature and camera, however it's really not that bad and you can definitely live with it, although some minigames are extremely difficult with just a keyboard. The camera feels stiff and awkward at times as well but it's manageable. My biggest gripe is easily the save feature, it does not auto save and you need to manually save at a telephone booth scattered around the map. If you're doing a long mission and the game crashes it's GG, you have to do it all over again, and some parts of dialogue are unskippable so yeah.  Other than those nuisances, this is a game that is worth far more than the price it's being sold at, and I would highly recommend getting this, even without a sale.", "appid": "638970", "steamid": "profiles/76561198082060532", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603713600.0}
