{"text": "Overall this game is awesome with the exception of the last boss. Stylish, great mechanics, and bosses that feel very unique and memorable from one another. I'm sure I don't even need to mention the legendary soundtrack which is just icing on the cake. I was fortunate enough to beat about half of the bosses on my first attempt, though that was only because I had seen others attempt the game before. I feel my run is a good example of how the bosses are far from impossible as long as you understand the mechanics and the optimal punishes for each one. Each boss has some way to exploit. Things like dashing behind them right after an attack is made on The Scale or using a charge slash to open them up after a large attack for The Hand and The Burst. The lives and health bars I did lose along the way however were never enough to deter me. Although I was filled with frustration many a time I constantly wanted to go back into the fight, feeling there was a legitimate way I could improve. I've never been good at bullet hell games, but feel fairly confident in my hack and slash skills. Each boss had an \"optimal\" strategy that made it easy, but I never felt like I had to fully deter from from my own game-plan completely as long as I adapted it. Sadly everything I love about this game feels like it was thrown away for the final boss, which is a pure bullet hell experience. I'm completely stuck on its last phase currently, and I am not sure if I even want to attempt to finish the game anymore. Not only are the mechanics that made me love the game in the first place suddenly gone, but the fight feels unnecessarily long and movement feels sluggish. Not to mention it shares the biggest gripe that I had with The Scale's final phase, that being that there isn't enough contrast between everything you are supposed to dodge. Even more frustrating is that even the floor is the same color as some of the bullets which makes them almost unnoticeable until they get close. Nothing about the experience feels enjoyable anymore at this point. All being said its still a great game, though I suggest people like me who prefer the action combat over the shooting combat choose the \"assimilation\" ending for the sake of their sanity as the last experience just feels like a let down. EDIT: After another 10 or so attempts I have finally beaten The Star, though my feelings about the boss itself remain unchanged.", "appid": "423230", "steamid": "profiles/76561198082760796", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603281600.0}
{"text": "Positives:      Game is very fun with teams of 5+.      Community is small but enjoyable.      Daily players. Negatives:      Reload bug that only happens once every so often.      Players only meet daily at a very specific time window, which ranges from 3-4 hours, 12pm-4pm EST             roughly.      Game feels very stale and boring if teams are less than 5 players.      Bots run into their own movement bugs, which breaks them often. Verdict:          Fantastic RTSFPS, has potential for a comeback if devs un-abandon the game and fix the few bugs and                add a few simple content updates for fun. Needs more players. Probably was incredibly fun in it's                prime.", "appid": "17710", "steamid": "profiles/76561198043431819", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "11", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1591444800.0}
